  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do keto gummies actually put you in ketosis?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Exogenous BHB (beta-hydroxybutyrate) gummies can temporarily elevate blood ketone levels, but they do not force your body into nutritional ketosis. True ketosis occurs when you restrict carbohydrates to fewer than 20-50g per day, causing your liver to produce ketones from stored fat. BHB gummies provide supplemental ketones that your body can use for energy, but they do not cause fat-derived ketone production. They are most useful during the transition period into ketosis (reducing "keto flu" symptoms), after occasional carb consumption (to return to ketone utilization faster), and as a quick energy source during fasted workouts.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How many carbs are in keto gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most keto gummies contain 1-4g of total carbohydrates per serving, with 0-3g of sugar. Some use sugar alcohols (erythritol, xylitol) or natural sweeteners (stevia, monk fruit) to minimize net carbs. For strict keto dieters consuming fewer than 20g net carbs daily, even 2-3g from gummies represents 10-15% of the daily carb budget. Sugar-free keto gummies with zero net carbs exist but may use sugar alcohols that cause digestive discomfort in some people. Always check the nutrition facts for total carbs, fiber, and sugar alcohols to calculate net carbs before purchasing.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is BHB in keto gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BHB (beta-hydroxybutyrate) is one of the three ketone bodies produced by your liver during ketosis. It is the most abundant circulating ketone, comprising approximately 78% of total blood ketones. Exogenous BHB in supplement form provides your body with ready-to-use ketones without requiring the liver to produce them from fat. BHB crosses the blood-brain barrier, providing an alternative energy source for the brain (which normally relies on glucose). Supplemental BHB is typically bound to sodium, calcium, or magnesium salts (BHB salts) for stability and absorption. Doses of 6-12g BHB salts can measurably elevate blood ketones within 30-60 minutes.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'When should I take keto gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The most strategic times to take keto gummies are: morning (to extend overnight fasting ketosis and provide energy without breaking carb restriction), before exercise (exogenous ketones provide energy for workouts without glucose), during the "keto flu" transition period (supplemental ketones reduce symptoms like headache, fatigue, and brain fog), and after accidental carb consumption (to return to ketone utilization faster). Do not take keto gummies as a substitute for dietary carb restriction — they are supplemental, not a replacement for the ketogenic diet itself.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do keto gummies help with weight loss?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Keto gummies do not directly cause weight loss. Weight loss on a ketogenic diet occurs through sustained carbohydrate restriction, which shifts the body to fat metabolism and often naturally reduces appetite. Keto gummies support this process by easing the keto transition (reducing "keto flu" that causes people to quit), providing ketone energy that reduces hunger, and supporting electrolyte balance disrupted by the low-insulin state. However, consuming exogenous ketones while still eating a high-carb diet will not produce weight loss — the body will simply use the supplemental ketones for energy while continuing to store dietary carbs as glycogen and fat.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are keto gummies safe?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'BHB salt gummies are generally safe for healthy adults. Common side effects include digestive discomfort (nausea, diarrhea) at high doses, which usually resolves as the body adapts. People with kidney disease should be cautious with BHB salts bound to potassium. Those with heart conditions should monitor sodium intake from sodium-bound BHB. Diabetics should consult their physician before using exogenous ketones, as they can interact with insulin and diabetes medications. Pregnant and breastfeeding women should avoid keto supplements. The ketogenic diet itself should ideally be undertaken with medical supervision, especially for people with existing health conditions.' } },
