    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Keto Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do keto gummies actually put you in ketosis?</summary><p>BHB gummies temporarily elevate blood ketones but do not force nutritional ketosis. True ketosis requires dietary carb restriction (fewer than 50g/day). BHB gummies help during transition (reducing keto flu), after carb intake, and as quick ketone energy.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How many carbs are in keto gummies?</summary><p>Most contain 1-4g total carbs per serving. Sugar-free options have 0-1g net carbs. For strict keto (fewer than 20g net carbs daily), even 2-3g represents 10-15% of your budget. Always check nutrition facts for net carb calculation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is BHB in keto gummies?</summary><p>Beta-hydroxybutyrate is the primary circulating ketone body (78% of blood ketones). Exogenous BHB provides ready-to-use ketones without liver production. BHB crosses the blood-brain barrier for brain fuel. Supplemental BHB is bound to mineral salts (sodium, magnesium, calcium).</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>When should I take keto gummies?</summary><p>Morning (extend overnight ketosis), before exercise (ketone energy), during keto flu transition (reduce symptoms), and after carb intake (return to ketone utilization faster). Not a substitute for dietary carb restriction.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do keto gummies help with weight loss?</summary><p>Not directly. Weight loss on keto comes from sustained carb restriction and fat metabolism. Keto gummies support the process by easing transition, reducing hunger, and maintaining electrolytes. Taking keto gummies while eating high-carb will not produce weight loss.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are keto gummies safe?</summary><p>BHB salts are safe for healthy adults. Common side effects: digestive discomfort at high doses. Caution for kidney disease (potassium BHB), heart conditions (sodium BHB), and diabetes (interacts with insulin). Consult physician before starting keto.</p></details>

